Michel Louvain,  (July 12, 1937 – April 14, 2021) was a Canadian singer most popular in the 1960s and 1970s.
In 1965 he was voted 'Mr. Radio–TV', Radio Canada's top show business personality, at the Gala des Artistes.
Louvain was born Michel Poulin in Thetford Mines, Quebec, on July 12, 1937.
Louvain began working as a master of ceremonies at a hotel in Laval when he was 20 years old.
He was later signed to Apex Records in the 1960s.
Over the next 20 years, Louvain made many recordings, including the hit songs "La Dame en bleu" and "Je déclare l'amour au monde entier".
His song "C'est Un Secret" reached #14 in the Canadian RPM Magazine Top 40, November 29, 1965.
He first performed in nightclubs, and, when his following grew more mature, in entertainment theatres.
In the 1980s, he staged grandiose music-hall shows, with female dancers and scenery, at the Place des Arts and across Quebec, including Autour du monde in 1984.
In the 1980s, he staged grandiose music-hall shows, with female dancers and scenery, at the Place des Arts and across Quebec, including Autour du monde in 1984.
Louvain was appointed Knight of the National Order of Quebec in 2010.
Five years later, he was named a Member of the Order of Canada.
In 2017, as a celebration of his 80th birthday, Louvain set out on a concert tour.
He released his 32nd album, La belle vie, in 2019.
He was scheduled to tour throughout Quebec from September 2021, beginning in his hometown Thetford Mines.
Louvain died in his sleep on the night of April 14, 2021, at the Hôpital de Verdun in Montreal.
Louvain died in his sleep on the night of April 14, 2021, at the Hôpital de Verdun in Montreal.
He was 83, and suffered from esophageal cancer, which he had been diagnosed with earlier that month.
He was in a 25-year relationship with Mario Théberge, although the couple did not officially marry until just a few days before Louvain's death in 2021.
